    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1980-01-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1980-01-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="145"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d145">
                <head>145. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d145fn1"
                        >Source: Carter Library, National Security Affairs, Staff Material, Middle
                        East File, Box 31, Subject File, Iran 1/11/80–1/31/80. Secret; Sensitive.
                        Copies were sent to S, D, P, <gloss target="#t_NEA_1">NEA</gloss>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_CCG_1">Cogan</persName> (<gloss target="#t_CIA_1"
                            >CIA</gloss>), and <persName corresp="#p_SG_1">Sick</persName> (<gloss
                            target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss>).</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1980-01-13">January 13, 1980</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CR_4">Cottam</persName>/<persName corresp="#p_GQS_1"
                            >Ghotbzadeh</persName> Conversation</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PH_1">Henry Precht</persName>, <gloss
                            target="#t_IWG_1">IWG</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CR_4">Richard Cottam</persName>, University of
                        Pittsburgh</item>
                </list>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_CR_4">Cottam</persName> reached <persName
                        corresp="#p_GQS_1">Ghotbzadeh</persName> early this morning after
                    considerable difficulty. The conversation was hard to follow as <persName
                        corresp="#p_GQS_1">Ghotbzadeh</persName> insisted on speaking in “code.”</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_GQS_1">Ghotbzadeh</persName> insisted that it was possible
                    to reach a settlement before the Iranian presidential elections. In fact, he
                    thinks a settlement would assure him of victory. He believes he has <persName
                        corresp="#p_KAR_1">Khomeini</persName>’s backing in reaching a settlement.
                    In the past, “85 different people” in Qom were telling <persName
                        corresp="#p_KAR_1">Khomeini</persName> how to handle the crisis. Now he
                    (Ghotbzadeh) is “in control.” <persName corresp="#p_CR_4">Cottam</persName>
                    interprets this to mean that <persName corresp="#p_KAR_1">Khomeini</persName>
                    nods affirmatively when <persName corresp="#p_GQS_1">Ghotbzadeh</persName> puts
                    an idea to him.</p>
                <p>Ghotbzadeh’s principal point was that he had great confidence in <persName
                        corresp="#p_WK_1">Waldheim</persName> and was anxious that we allow
                        <persName corresp="#p_WK_1">Waldheim</persName> to set the pace for a
                    settlement. Our pressure for sanctions was making it very hard for <persName
                        corresp="#p_GQS_1">Ghotbzadeh</persName> to maneuver. We should listen to
                        <persName corresp="#p_WK_1">Waldheim</persName>, the Iranians were taking
                    their lead from him. <persName corresp="#p_CR_4">Cottam</persName> said he had
                    the impression that <persName corresp="#p_WK_1">Waldheim</persName> was
                    developing proposals which included a delay on the vote on sanctions but we were
                    not listening to <persName corresp="#p_WK_1">Waldheim</persName> and the effect
                    was to restrict Ghotbzadeh’s freedom of maneuver. <persName corresp="#p_GQS_1"
                        >Ghotbzadeh</persName> said he had complete confidence in <persName
                        corresp="#p_FM_1">Farhang</persName> who spoke for him.</p>
                <p>A second principal point was Ghotbzadeh’s emphasis on extradition from Panama.
                        <persName corresp="#p_CR_4">Cottam</persName> said he questioned him sharply
                    asking him whether extradition was a realistic consideration or just something
                    in Ghotbzadeh’s mind. <persName corresp="#p_GQS_1">Ghotbzadeh</persName> replied
                    that he was very confident of what he was saying because he had spoken directly
                    to Panamanian leaders. Nevertheless it was not clear to <persName
                        corresp="#p_CR_4">Cottam</persName> whether <persName corresp="#p_GQS_1"
                        >Ghotbzadeh</persName> was talking about extradition or an extradition
                    trial. <persName corresp="#p_GQS_1">Ghotbzadeh</persName> made two comments to
                        <persName corresp="#p_CR_4">Cottam</persName> on Panama. First, all the
                    Americans have to do “is to give Panama the green light and they will go ahead
                    as planned.” Second, perhaps the U.S. should send “the same man” down there to
                        <pb facs="0433" n="384" xml:id="pg_384"/> discuss the crisis with Panama.
                    There was no indication who this might be.</p>
                <p>I asked <persName corresp="#p_CR_4">Cottam</persName> whether the Panama track
                    seemed an essential part of Ghotbzadeh’s plan. He said it clearly was but it did
                    not seem to be linked in timing or substance to the <gloss target="#t_UN_1"
                        >UN</gloss> activity. There plainly had to be some movement in Panama,
                    possibly for an extradition trial, for <persName corresp="#p_GQS_1"
                        >Ghotbzadeh</persName> to succeed.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_CR_4">Cottam</persName> asked <persName corresp="#p_GQS_1"
                        >Ghotbzadeh</persName> about the linkage between Afghanistan and the
                    hostages and whether an argument could be made to <persName corresp="#p_KAR_1"
                        >Khomeini</persName> that once the hostage issue was over, Iran could assume
                    a world role in opposing the Soviets. <persName corresp="#p_GQS_1"
                        >Ghotbzadeh</persName> said Afghanistan was still important to him and
                    others on the Revolutionary Council but it was not an effective argument with
                        <persName corresp="#p_KAR_1">Khomeini</persName>. <persName
                        corresp="#p_GQS_1">Ghotbzadeh</persName> had gotten into some trouble within
                    the “party” because of his strong statement on Afghanistan.</p>
                <p>In closing, <persName corresp="#p_GQS_1">Ghotbzadeh</persName> reemphasized that
                    he was very positive on <persName corresp="#p_WK_1">Waldheim</persName> who he
                    thought was handling the crisis well. It could be ended in ten days if we
                    relaxed on sanctions.</p>
            </div>
